aa(lp48
VWhen I was 17, I visited Dr. Schlaug's lab, and in one afternoon
p49
aVhe walked me through some of the leading research
p50
aVon music and the brain \u2014 how musicians had
p51
aVfundamentally different brain structure than non-musicians,
p52
aVhow music, and listening to music,
p53
aVcould just light up the entire brain, from
p54
aVour prefrontal cortex all the way back to our cerebellum,
p55
aVhow music was becoming a neuropsychiatric modality
p56
aVto help children with autism, to help people struggling
p57
aVwith stress and anxiety and depression,
p58
aVhow deeply Parkinsonian patients would find that their tremor
p59
aVand their gait would steady when they listened to music,
p60
aVand how late-stage Alzheimer's patients, whose dementia
p61
aVwas so far progressed that they could no longer recognize
p62
aVtheir family, could still pick out a tune by Chopin
p63
aVat the piano that they had learned when they were children.
